Exercise 1 - describing the dataset and making some initial plots

  1. Describe the dataset, such that someone who happened upon this dataset could understand the variables and what they contain

The researchers are investigating whether pitch varies according to the setting a person is in - formal or informal. The experiment is performed on Koreans who now live in America. We have a dataset with 224 observations and seven coloums to describe each observation. The seven variable are: - Subject. All the matching names are one subject. - Gender. Pretty self-explanatory. - Scenario. The subjects are presented to seven different scenarios. - Attitude. Whether it is the formal or informal condition of the scenario. Each participant goes through both. - Total duration. Amount of time the subject uses to complete the scenario. - f0mn. Mean pitch (in Hz). - hiss count. Some sound might say while speaking (loud breath intakes).

i. Also consider whether any of the variables in _politeness_ should be encoded as factors or have the factor encoding removed. Hint: ```?factor```

Gender and attitude.

Interpretation when scenario is integer: Scenario is treated as something continuous that can have any value on a number scale.

Interpretation when scenario is factor: Scenario is treated as something where we have a limited set of possible values (specifically the seven scenarios we see in the data set). So a scenario either is one of the seven or not, and R gives us a TRUE/FALSE (where 1 is true and 0 is false) answer to all of the seven possibilities.

  1. Build four models and do some comparisons
    1. a single level model that models f0mn as dependent on gender
    2. a two-level model that adds a second level on top of i. where unique intercepts are modelled for each scenario
    3. a two-level model that only has subject as an intercept
    4. a two-level model that models intercepts for both scenario and subject
pacman::p_load(lmerTest)
model1 <- lm(f0mn~gender, politeness)
model2 <- lmerTest::lmer(f0mn~gender + (1|scenario), politeness)
model3 <- lmerTest::lmer(f0mn~gender + (1|subject), politeness)
model4 <- lmerTest::lmer(f0mn~gender + (1|scenario) + (1|subject), politeness)

Seems like model 5 and 6 are very similar, so I would always penalize the more complicated one. Model4 is not far off though But model5 includes attitude, which is pretty relevant to the research questions, sooooo thats gonna be hard to come around.

  1. Choose the model that you think describe the data the best - and write a short report on the main findings based on this model. At least include the following: I choose model 5, since its the simplest model that does the best in the comparison. Also, when making the models with lmerTest and then running summary, both of the main effects are significant, but the interaction isnt.

  1. describe what the dataset consists of
    The model looks like this: model5 <- lmer(f0mn~gender + attitude + (1|scenario) + (1|subject), politeness) It consists of two fixed effects being gender and attitude. This is where we expect systematic variance. We also include random intercepts based on scenario and subject. This is where we expect variance, that we cant model systematically. The model is made from the politeness dataset.

  2. what can you conclude about the effect of gender and attitude on pitch (if anything)?
    Not sure how to interpret IF we can conclude anything. Especially not about other people than the specific participants here But if we can, then:

  • Men generally have a pitch that is 115.4 Hz (with a standard error of 12.9) lower than womens.

  • Being in the formal condition will lower pitch with 14.8 (standard error of 4.1) Hz. So the participants speak a bit deeper, when they are being polite.

    1. motivate why you would include separate intercepts for subjects and scenarios (if you think they should be included)
      I think both should be included, especially for subjects. I expect a lot of variance coming from the fact that people have way different baseline pitches. I also expect people to have different pitches based on condition - e.g.I would maybe speak lower/deeper in a library than in a classroom. But I expect this effect to have less impact than subject.

    2. describe the variance components of the second level (if any)
      The variance is the squared deviation. The exact numbers can be how to interpret, because they depend on the dataset, but we can see that a lot of the varieace is explained by the fixed and random effects, which is a good thing.
